<h1 class="title">Legal Document</h1>
</header>
<h1 id="in-the-superior-court-of-camden-county">IN THE SUPERIOR COURT OF
CAMDEN COUNTY</h1>
<h1 id="state-of-georgia">STATE OF GEORGIA</h1>
<p>CHRISTYN E. JOHNSON, Plaintiff,</p>
<ol start="22" type="a">
<li></li>
</ol>
<p>WILLIAM R. JOHNSON, Defendant.</p>
<p>CIVIL ACTION FILE NO. 2025CV936</p>
<p><strong>DEFENDANT’S VERIFIED MOTION TO SEAL RECORD AND REDACT MINOR’S
PII (OPSEC PROTOCOL)</strong></p>
<p>COMES NOW, William R. Johnson, Defendant Pro Se, and respectfully
submits this Motion to Seal and Redact all documents containing the full
names and personally identifiable information of the minor children in
this case.</p>
<h2 id="i.-introduction">I. INTRODUCTION</h2>
<p>This Motion seeks to protect the privacy and safety of the minor
children, Sebastian Johnson (DOB: 2016) and Willow Johnson (DOB: 2016),
who are innocent third parties in this litigation. The public disclosure
of their full names and personal information creates an unacceptable
risk of identity theft, data commodification, and potential harm in the
digital age.</p>
<h2 id="ii.-jurisdictional-authority">II. JURISDICTIONAL AUTHORITY</h2>
<p>This Court has inherent authority to seal court records and protect
the privacy of minor children pursuant to: - Uniform Superior Court Rule
21 (Privacy Protection) - Georgia Code § 19-7-11 (Records of Juvenile
Proceedings) - Georgia Code § 19-9-77 (Records of Juvenile Proceedings)
- Inherent judicial authority to protect vulnerable parties</p>
<h2 id="iii.-factual-background">III. FACTUAL BACKGROUND</h2>
<h3 id="a.-minor-childrens-status">A. Minor Children’s Status</h3>
<p>The minor children, Sebastian Johnson and Willow Johnson, are
innocent third parties who: 1. Have no legal capacity to consent to
public disclosure of their personal information 2. Are not parties to
this litigation 3. Have fundamental privacy rights that must be
protected 4. Are particularly vulnerable to identity theft and online
exploitation</p>
<h3 id="b.-current-privacy-breach">B. Current Privacy Breach</h3>
<p>The current court record contains numerous documents that expose the
children’s full names and personal information, including: - Pleadings
and motions - Financial affidavits - Medical records - School records -
Any other documents containing the children’s full names</p>
<h3 id="c.-risk-assessment">C. Risk Assessment</h3>
<p>In the current digital environment, public disclosure of minor
children’s PII creates significant risks: 1. <strong>Identity
Theft</strong>: Children are prime targets for identity theft due to
their clean credit histories 2. <strong>Data Commodification</strong>:
Personal information is bought and sold by data brokers 3.
<strong>Online Predation</strong>: Public records can be accessed by
individuals with malicious intent 4. <strong>Future Harm</strong>:
Digital footprints created now can affect the children’s future
opportunities</p>
<h2 id="iv.-legal-argument">IV. LEGAL ARGUMENT</h2>
<h3 id="a.-childrens-privacy-rights">A. Children’s Privacy Rights</h3>
<p>Georgia courts recognize that children have fundamental privacy
rights that must be protected. <em>In re Doe</em>, 290 Ga. 40 (2011).
The state has a compelling interest in protecting children from harm,
including the harm caused by inappropriate disclosure of personal
information.</p>
<h3 id="b.-public-interest-in-privacy">B. Public Interest in
Privacy</h3>
<p>The public interest strongly favors protecting children’s privacy
over any minimal public benefit from accessing their personal
information. The children are not public figures, and their personal
information serves no legitimate public purpose.</p>
<h3 id="c.-uniform-superior-court-rule-21-compliance">C. Uniform
Superior Court Rule 21 Compliance</h3>
<p>Uniform Superior Court Rule 21.1 provides that “the court may, upon
motion, order that any document or portion thereof be sealed if the
court finds that the public interest in access to the document or
portion thereof is outweighed by the interest in keeping the document or
portion thereof confidential.”</p>
<p>The factors to consider include: 1. Whether disclosure would create a
clear danger of physical harm 2. Whether disclosure would create a clear
danger of financial harm 3. Whether the information is already publicly
available 4. Whether the information involves minors</p>
<p>All factors strongly favor sealing in this case.</p>
<h2 id="v.-relief-requested">V. RELIEF REQUESTED</h2>
<p>WHEREFORE, Defendant respectfully requests this Honorable Court:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>SEAL</strong> all documents in the court record that contain
the full names and PII of Sebastian Johnson and Willow Johnson</li>
<li><strong>ORDER</strong> that all future filings redact the children’s
full names, using only initials (S.J. and W.J.)</li>
<li><strong>DIRECT</strong> the Clerk of Court to maintain sealed copies
of all affected documents</li>
<li><strong>PROHIBIT</strong> any party from filing documents containing
the children’s full names without prior court approval</li>
<li><strong>GRANT</strong> such other relief as the Court deems just and
proper</li>
</ol>
<h2 id="vi.-verification">VI. VERIFICATION</h2>
<p>I, William R. Johnson, being duly sworn, depose and say that I am the
Defendant in this action; that I have read the foregoing Motion; that
the facts stated therein are true and correct to the best of my
knowledge, information, and belief.</p>
